7392 #ifdef _MSC_VER
7393 #define FOR_EACH_2(MACRO_TO_INVOKE, ...) C2(FOR_EACH_2_, C1(COUNT_ARG(__VA_ARGS__))) LPAREN MACRO_TO_INVOKE, __VA_ARGS__)
7394 /*the COUNTED breed of FOR_EACH macro invokes a macro with 3 parameters: 1st being the count of invocation. For example.
7395 FOR_EACH_2_COUNTER(MACRO, a,b,c,d,e,f) will result in
7396 MACRO(6, a,b)
7397 MACRO(4, c,d)
7398 MACRO(2, e,f)
7399 This macro exists because we need a "stop condition" in outputting COMMA... when calling a function f(a,b,c,d) cannot be f(a,b,c,d,) <=doesn't compile (as opposed to enum definition)
7400 */
7401 #define FOR_EACH_2_COUNTED(MACRO_TO_INVOKE, ...) C2(FOR_EACH_2_COUNTED_, C1(COUNT_ARG(__VA_ARGS__))) LPAREN MACRO_TO_INVOKE, __VA_ARGS__)
7402 #define FOR_EACH_1_COUNTED(MACRO_TO_INVOKE, ...) C2(FOR_EACH_1_COUNTED_, C1(COUNT_ARG(__VA_ARGS__))) LPAREN MACRO_TO_INVOKE, __VA_ARGS__)

7404 /*FOR_EACH_2_REVERSE acts just like FOR_EACH_2, but in reverse order. Example:
7405 FOR_EACH_2_REVERSE(X,a,b,c,d,e,f) => X(e,f) X(c,d) X (a, b) in this order */
7406 #define FOR_EACH_2_REVERSE(MACRO_TO_INVOKE, ...) C2(FOR_EACH_2_REVERSE_, C1(COUNT_ARG(__VA_ARGS__))) LPAREN MACRO_TO_INVOKE, __VA_ARGS__)
7407 #else
